    <title>Combined summary - Open Block Chain Licence, BIP[xxxx] Draft</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T21:49:13.521918+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-September/010818.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin network has been facing a licensing issue related to the copyright ownership of transaction messages that are being published by various parties. There is concern that publishing these messages and reproducing them in blocks may potentially violate copyright laws. It is unclear who the copyright owners are in this scenario, and whether miners have permission to republish messages. Additionally, transaction malleability creates derivative works with multiple copyright holders, which further complicates the issue.Ahmed Zsales proposed a draft BIP for discussion and evaluation regarding the need for a block chain license to supplement the existing MIT License, which only covers the core reference client software. The proposal aims to address issues of copyright ownership and licensing for data existing before a license change. However, some members of the bitcoin-dev mailing list have raised concerns about licensing after the fact as it requires the permission of every copyright holder in order to make the change, making it an impossible task. Furthermore, Warren Togami Jr. expressed skepticism that any license for the blockchain itself is needed because it might not be entitled to copyright protection.Despite these concerns, there is a suggestion that a block chain license may be necessary to supplement the existing MIT License. The proposed solution is to give miners the main benefits of licensing and let them vote to adopt new terms, although it is unclear if this would be successful or if anyone has suffered economic losses due to the current situation. The authors of the draft BIP believe that a block chain license is necessary to supplement the existing MIT License, which only covers core reference client software. However, further investigation and legal consultation are recommended before proceeding with any licensing agreements.The discussion on the bitcoin-dev mailing list also involves proposing a block chain license to supplement the existing MIT License. The proposal raises concerns about licensing after the fact, which requires permission from every copyright holder to make any changes. It was suggested that miners be the main beneficiaries of licensing, and they should vote to adopt the new terms. However, there are concerns that such a proposal would be impossible since every existing transaction author and miner who published a block would have to agree to the terms for them to be legal.Despite these issues, the speaker acknowledges that there doesn't seem to be anyone who could claim to have suffered any economic losses so this may not be an issue. The general consensus seems to be that further investigation and discussion is needed before any decisions can be made regarding licensing the blockchain.In a discussion on the bitcoin-dev mailing list, Ahmed Zsales suggested that a block chain license is required for the network. The group also considered references to protections for private keys while they remain under your control and whether or not finding private keys attached to coins and moving the funds constituted theft. However, the decision was made not to include anything specific in the draft license to keep it simple, relying instead on generic definitions of rights to private transaction data which would cover private keys. Further investigation is needed to determine if this proposal is feasible.The Bitcoin community has received a proposal for an Open Block Chain Licence, which some believe is necessary to supplement the existing MIT Licence. However, there are concerns that such a licence would be pointless as Bitcoin cannot be controlled and it would not stand up in court. The statement that users pay to use the network but have no defined rights is a feature of Bitcoin, not a bug. This is because if users had rights to sue someone, then the system would not be decentralized.</summary>
